IBM’s History: From the Cheese Cutter to Space Flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 - originally it was a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation that gave rise to IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
It possessed inventions such as the famous "clock to record", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint hired the head of a competitor company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The new leader overshadowed the IBM founder (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson led the company, revenue doubled by $9 million and the company’s massive expansion across continents began.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after almost forty years in the chair of the boss, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the standard of computers of that time, came to the market under the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, in turn, acquired the consultancy part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer comprehensive advice and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for these last three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, “a smarter planet”.
Its aim is to make a more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned and circumstances have not been improved, for example, in relation to transport and city administration.
For the retail sector, IBM recently unveiled the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the entire trading cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 it opened a branch in Czechoslovakia at the time, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
