How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia at the time: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time sold in most cases only trips to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and Czech tourist trips were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies in those times also offered trips to the West, but one had to queue up with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired.
The Czechs’ way of travelling has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware, that the currently favourite destination, Croatia, could not be travelled freely until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa waivers were imposed for travel to neighbouring Western European states, leading to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see themselves fed up with excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in parks in tents, as our income back then did not allow us to pay for a hotel or board.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take food (canned food, sausages, etc.) with them to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech krona, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy western currency.
Our standard of living was rising and with it also the average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in demand for travel agencies began, from 1997 on a regular basis, to prepare travel using charter flight connections, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for passenger volume.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs were traveling visa-free to almost every developed country except the U.S., which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened as early as 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czechia to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists depart every year to distant and hot countries. This winter will already fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than 15,000 CZK on travel abroad per head, including expenses on the place of stay.
