The relocated pavilion
by Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups and downs and a happy ending, the pavilion of the 1958 Austrian Universal Exhibition in Brussels won awards, was in Vienna for a museum, became empty and collapsed.
It is now reopened as an exhibition house.
Modern postgerra architecture is passionate about clear shapes, glass halls, bold curves and new building materials, typical of thinking about technical progress, for which the Austrian pavilion of architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels Universal Exhibition is a suitable and well-known example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel and glass construction.
The construction is considered to this day a contemporary landmark of architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built the Austrian pavilion at the following world exhibition.
With its legendary four-cylinder tower for MBW plus the adjacent flattened building in Munich, it became internationally known.
Its pavilion, designed as a temporary construction for exhibitions was erected after the universal exhibition in the Schweizer Garten next to the South Station in Vienna, was renovated in 1962 and inside a 20th-century museum was opened, it was called the "House 20".
The building was adequate but lacked the right spaces and technology for a museum; no wall to hang art, no good atmosphere.
Despite this, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna had a new home.
The building has been empty since 2001 and is decaying more and more.
Currently, the architect Adolf Krischanitz reformed the pavilion, now calling it "house 21" and will be used in the future as a museum of contemporary art.
On Tuesday afternoon the belvedere museum, to which the house belongs, was inaugurated, with the first exhibition, a stroke of luck in a way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, the new director of the Austrian belvedere since 2007, has made a fresh start.
Husslein-Arco, a doctor of art history with a considerable career, among other things, an artistic ice skater in her youth, later in Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, carried out the reforms at the insistence of politicians and protectors of the monuments, provided public funds and private sponsors and established their use.
With the exception of contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba of the foundation of the same name are exhibited, there should be a cafeteria and a bookstore, and an office building should be built.
Strict control, low budget
Krischanitz was the best choice to do so.
Not only because he significantly reformed the secession of Joseph Olbrichs in Vienna, expanded it and was awarded the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzwer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him an "important and immense place", in which he contemplated "almost every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the project and the problem of the building, which disappeared with its transfer to Vienna in its change of use with generosity and ease.
In the current renovations there are big problems, the building was "an energy eater," Krischanitz said.
The profile of the glass facade windows was changed, an insulating glass reinforced with fiberglass was installed, and the glass ceiling was replaced with a special safety glass.
Thermal bridges and steel beams were reinforced or replaced and asbestos roofs were rehabilitated.
Two basements were used for the new use, a light panel descended between the house and the street provides lighting, a bridge serves to enter the almost new building, but still the Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain, the house is painted in antique mahogany tones and protected from rust.
And the movie theater is exactly as it was before.
And all this with strict control by the monuments office and a low budget.
“I often had to find material that was good, cheap and also liked the monument protection office,” says Krischanitz and warns of a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the pressures, problems and renovations, the building remains flexible and lightweight.
