“I oppose the court because it was mandated by organizations that support hate ideology and because it supports multiculturalism.”
"I acknowledge the facts but do not plead guilty."
Judge Torkjel Nesheim interrupted Breivik during that monologue, because “I didn’t want to give Breivik the opportunity to use this hearing as a platform for him to express his views.”
For the same reason he refused to allow Breivik, who brought a written speech in advance, to address the relatives of his victims at the end of the hearing.
Nesheim also ordered police to keep Breivik in custody for another 12 weeks, banned him from accessing the media for four weeks, and said authorities would have to have strict control over all visits and correspondence for eight weeks.
About 30 survivors and relatives of the victims attended the hearing.
Some came hoping to look Breivik in the eye, others to confirm that he is locked up.
All attended with the aim of advancing towards the conclusion.
“I thought it looked cold and inhuman,” one survivor from Utoya told Norwegian broadcaster NRK.
"It was uncomfortable, but for me it was a step forward after seeing and hearing the suspect."
