It may comfort some that the July 22 attacks appear to be the work of an extremist rather than a group of radicals.
But that doesn’t automatically ease the pain and confusion that an entire nation still feels.
“I’d like it to look like a monster, but it doesn’t look like it,” said a relative of a victim.
"It would be a lot easier if it looked like it."
7 Lessons From Steve Jobs' Lost Interview Showed At A Theater This Week
After Steve Jobs’ death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford – distinguishing the tech genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been dusted off as a preview of a series of special screenings in the biggest markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was certainly a designer, dreamer, and self-recognized hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a flowchart yoki — a man who believed that many executives suffered “a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds over the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for over an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At the time, it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively on his new computer company NeXT, waiting for popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used on Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during her transport.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly re-released footage is the basis for Steve Jobs: The Lost 68-minute Interview, which hits Landmark theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers — from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, looking for precision.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringely’s questions, pushing him to go faster toward the topics or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies do right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous reviews of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
“Throughout the years in the business, I always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers they invariably give you are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
Nobody knows why he does what he does, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs takes into detail his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Bewildered by the way costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was done at a glance, and then adjusted with a "variable" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine retail commercial costs.
The Joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" he built himself with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been written extensively about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a public telephone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and you yelled through the pay phone and then came back a minute later to the pay phone next door,” Jobs says with a chuckle.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us, we didn’t know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing — it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost leave, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope, while making his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling over the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call to him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode-ray tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a ride to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he dedicated himself to selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a customer if he could assemble the whole equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got tired and went outside and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and it was totally reliable.
On the big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s renaissance, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble into his vision, and lose control of their market share.
“Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers and printers, so what?”
You have a monopoly of market share, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is this kind of people who end up leading companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the forum for decision-making.
The genius of the products that led to that position of monopoly is rotten by the fault of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
Innovation as an Artistic Expression:
“There’s a huge amount of work going on between a great idea and a great product...as the great idea evolves, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make – some things you can’t make electrons do, glass does them, robots do them, factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end it all boils down to taste – it boils down to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to tailor those things to what you’re doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have never been ashamed of stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren’t for computer science, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas Dine with Health Care Law Rivals as Court Accepts Case
The day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to examine the politically controversial question of whether they would accept President Obama’s challenge to the health care law, two of his magistrates, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were groomed at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will expose the case to the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to thoroughly study the requests for review.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging total health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying cry for conservative activists across the country.
The magistrates agreed to admit the lawsuit to trial and, in fact, a historic 5-and-a-half-hour pleading is expected by March, and the outcome is likely to further cloud the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court’s decision is known.
The attorney who will appear in court and argue that the law should be scrapped will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. attorney general during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement’s law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual Federalist Society dinner, a group that has been dedicated to defending conservative legal principles for many years.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that defied the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel, hours after the court's preliminary hearing on the case.
Attendees included, among others, Mitch McConnell, the top Republican in the Senate and an outspoken opponent of the health care law.
The special guests at dinner, Scalia and Thomas.
It’s nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it is not something that conflicts with ethical norms.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct that governs the actions of lower federal judges.
If they were not, they could be said to fall under Canon Code 4C, which says, “A judge may attend events to raise funds from law-related organizations and others, although the judge may not be a speaker, an honorary guest, or appear on the program of such an event.”
However, Scalia and Thomas’ absolute proximity to two of the law firms in the case, as well as to a company with a huge financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in the government.
“This impressive breach of ethics and indifference to the code runs counter to the lawsuits of several magistrates that the court abides by the same rules that apply to all federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"The judges were harassed at a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have cases pending in court."
Their appearance and assistance in raising funds for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in criticism that they say mix too easily the court’s activity with the agenda driven by groups like the Federalist Society.
And Thomas’ wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it is magistrate Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as the Obama administration’s attorney general when the first legal challenges to the law were presented in the court of first instance.
Her critics have pushed for Kagan to refrain from seeing the case, saying she was too involved in defending the law to now be impartial.
Kagan has given no indication that he will do so.
Boeing Receives Record Order of $18 Billion
Emirates is ordering 50 Boeing 777 twin-aisle aircraft, with an option for 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliner aircraft to Oman Air, an operation valued at more than $1 billion.
Rarely is it news when a company gets an order for 50 units of its product.
But it’s a big deal when the company is the aircraft maker Boeing Co. and the sale price for the 50 aircraft amounts to a record $18 billion.
It is as big as the place from where Boeing received the order: the Middle East, a growing gold mine of future aircraft orders.
In a study released Monday, the Chicago-based airline estimates that over the next 20 years, airlines in the Middle East will need 2,520 aircraft worth $450 billion.
Boeing announced over the weekend its largest ever order for commercial aircraft by its dollar value - 50 Boing 777 twin-aisle jets.
The successful order came from the Emirates airline in Dubai.
The airline also has an option to buy 20 more aircraft, which would raise the total selling price to $26 billion, Boeing announced at the 2011 Dubai Airshow.
Then on Monday, Boeing said Oman Air had ordered six Boeing 787-8s, the so-called Dreamliner, which boasts spectacular fuel savings and passenger services.
The selling price for six of them is more than a billion dollars.
“This clearly has a huge positive effect for Boeing,” said Morningstar analyst Neal Dihora.
"The quality of these particular customers is very strong."
Many Middle Eastern airlines are owned by their oil-producing nations.
Therefore, not only do they have the money to pay for the planes, but an increase in fuel prices - usually detrimental to airlines, because it is one of the highest costs - is not so detrimental, because the country is making money with the increase in the price of oil.
That’s important because they’re less likely than other airlines to cancel or delay flight orders when fuel prices rise, Dihora said.
“They have natural protection,” he said.
The UAE order solidifies Boeing’s leadership in the wide-body aircraft market and helps keep at bay its competitor Airbus SAS’ attempt to invade its dominance with the A350 passenger jet.
Boeing’s victory at the air show comes four months after Airbus said it would delay the debut of the larger A350, which competes directly with the 777-300ER.
It delayed the debut to add more momentum after customers demanded an increase in payload and range.
Shares of Boeing Co rose 1.5% to $67.94.
The sister of the president of Mexico, apparently defeated in the vote of Michoacán
Luisa María Calderón claims that the drug traffickers helped her PRI opponent, Fausto Vallejo, in the gubernatorial contest.
President Felipe Calderón's sister appears to have lost her candidacy for governor of Michoacán during the state's violent election, and she said Monday that drug traffickers helped tilt the race in favor of one of her opponents.
The preliminary results gave the lead in the race for governor of the western state to Fausto Vallejo, of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
"The intervention of organized crime throughout the electoral process and, especially yesterday, is alarming, not only for Michoacán, but for the whole country," Luisa María Calderón said in a radio interview a day after Sunday's vote.
“They threatened our candidates, our election workers... They seized the ballot boxes, they installed barricades... and they ordered the people to vote” in favor of the PRI.
The PRI ruled Mexico for seven decades until it lost the presidency in 2000.
However, it is the staging of a comeback, and the victory in Michoacán is an important step in that effort.
The PRI hopes to win the presidential election in July.
Vallejo seems to have narrowly overtaken Calderon, who had led the polls before the election.
Calderón, a candidate for his brother's conservative National Action Party, or PAN, refused to recognize Vallejo as the winner.
Silvano Aureoles, the leftist candidate for the Democratic Revolution Party, or PRD, which currently holds the position of governor, came in third place, a major defeat for the divided and unfortunate left before the 2012 presidential elections.
Aureoles also refused to acknowledge the preliminary results.
Vallejo, a former mayor of the state capital of Morelia, denied links to drug trafficking and urged other candidates to accept the results.
Michoacán has long been dominated by drug cartels specializing in marijuana, heroin and methamphetamines.
It is the home state of President Calderón, and he chose Michoacán to launch a military offensive directed against traffickers in December 2006.
However, the violence has persisted.
A PAN mayor was killed a week before the election while campaigning for Luisa María Calderón, and numerous candidates abandoned local candidacies out of fear.
Although for the PRI, as unpleasant as Michoacán’s elections may seem, a victory will help boost the party.
The man who is supposed to represent the PRI in the presidential election, Enrique Peña Nieto, speaking from Washington, congratulated Vallejo and said: "I think this victory should be very encouraging, for next year."
AfDB Urges Asia to Help Rescue Eurozone
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has called on India and China to prepare to help rescue the eurozone from its sovereign debt crisis to avoid a long-term recession that would hamper the growth of Asian economies.
Rajat Nag, Managing Director of the Manila-based Asian Development Bank, said the world’s two fastest-growing major economies had to “do everything possible” to accelerate the economic bloc’s recovery either through the International Monetary Fund or directly through bilateral agreements.
He warned against BRIC countries looking at Europe’s difficulties in an “impartial” way and said Asia’s financial assistance along with European leadership and resources would help avert a long-term crisis in the global economy.
"We're all in this together."
“So anyone who can help Europe out of the crisis is useful,” he told the Financial Times in an interview at the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
“Asia can be protected to some extent, but it can’t be immune.”
"So if China and India can help, let it be by all means."
The European monetary union has been severely undermined by a sovereign debt crisis in recent months.
In recent days, Italy’s borrowing costs have skyrocketed dangerously and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The current sovereign debt crisis in Europe has raised fears that it could push the global economy into recession and has generated calls for major emerging economies to come together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that any support from Asia would be channelled through the IMF, but said bilateral assistance – such as buying bonds from the EU bailout fund, the European Financial Stability Fund – offered greater bargaining power for Europe’s Asian partners.
Anand Sharma, India’s trade minister, said “India is going to do everything it can” to help the eurozone as its own economy was now suffering from falling exports and depletion of foreign capital inflows.
“Nobody wants the eurozone to remain unstable and turbulent,” he said.
"We have monumental challenges and we have to maintain a high level of growth."
“It’s not an option, it’s an imperative, because where do we find employment for tens of millions of our young men and women?”
Others argue that developing economies like India have no responsibility to help wealthy Europeans when facing their own deep economic problems.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the U.S., said it would be politically very difficult to sell aid to Europe for India’s one billion two hundred thousand people, of whom up to 800 million live on about $2 a day or less.
“At some point they will realize that Greeks are retiring at the age of 50 and going on vacation to the beaches and that won’t do well,” he said.
Lee Howell, managing director of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India’s reserves should be used to keep Greece’s numerous, well-paid public sector workers in jobs in poorly managed, loss-making companies like the railways.
Mr Nag said the eurozone crisis threatened "significant chain effects" across Asia.
The Asian Development Bank’s forecast of 7.5 percent economic growth in Asia for 2011/12 now faces “downside risks” due to the threat from Europe.
He said vulnerable emerging markets needed to make “contingency plans” to protect themselves from a crisis and significant capital outflows from their economies.
Pentagon Warnings of Possible Defense Cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta warmed Congress on Monday, warning that upcoming automatic budget cuts could undermine national security and spark a financial chain reaction from Pentagon corridors to Afghanistan’s battlefields to civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon is already digesting the $450 billion in cuts over the next decade, but now fears an additional $600 billion or more in cuts that may be imminent if Congress fails to agree on spending.
“The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the department,” Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, Republican for Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, Republican for South Carolina.
He said the failure of Congress to reach an agreement on the budget and its consequence, the so-called “kidnapping,” would result in 23 percent global cuts and a halt to many new projects.
“Such a large cut, applied in this indiscriminate way, would make most of our naval and construction projects impossible to execute – you can’t buy three-quarters of a ship or a building – and seriously damage other modernization efforts,” Panetta wrote to the senators.
“We would also be forced to involuntarily remove many of our civilian officials and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, it is almost certain that we would have to dismiss civilians in order to meet the goal.”
“These changes would break the faith with those who maintain our army and seriously damage the goodwill.”
The cuts over time would hit combat troops, Panetta said.
“While wartime funding in the overseas contingency Operations accounts is not directly affected by the kidnapping, war efforts would be adversely affected by severe disruptions in baseline budgets,” Panetta warned.
"The hiring of personnel would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and oversight of the contract supporting the war."
"Payment staff would be reduced, leading to delays in payments to suppliers in time of war, and legal and political support would be interrupted."
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days ago, asking for information about the possible impact of automatic cuts on the Department of Defense.
“The aftermath of a kidnapping in the Department of Defense would result in a rapid decline of the United States as the world’s leading military power.”
"We are firmly against this draconian action," the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they published Panetta's letter.
“This is not an outcome that we can live with, and it is certainly not one that we should impose on ourselves.”
“The kidnapping is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not be allowed to happen.”
Whether Panetta’s letter and recent warnings from senators will increase pressure for a budget commitment or intensify calls to exempt the Pentagon from the cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly outspoken about possible cuts, even though he came to a job at the top of the Pentagon with years of experience in budgeting in Congress and the White House and knowing he was facing difficult decisions.
At a press conference last week, the secretary of defense painted a bleak picture of what might be ahead — an army with a shell, but not a core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a bulletless brigade."
"It's an air wing without enough trained pilots."
“It’s a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough trained soldiers to fulfill the mission,” Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a force that suffers from low morale, poor preparation and is not able to keep up with potential adversaries."
"Indeed, it invites aggression..."
In an appendix to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta lays out new details of how the reductions “generate significant operational risks: delays in response time to crises, conflicts and disasters; severely limits our ability to be deployed and previously engaged worldwide; and poses an unacceptable risk in future combat operations.”
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could tackle the axe, including those already being tested and some only in the early stages of planning.
That list includes the F35 Joint Strike Fighter, a new planned bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new coastal combat ship and the new ground combat vehicle that the Army and Navy need to replace, the humvee.
Stopping further development and testing of the F35 could generate about $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it’s the vital next step to improving and tackling potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Detect a Lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment allegations with several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “caught” with an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a mockery of his denials quickly rebuffed by the irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps are widespread in school and college exams.
There have been cases where teachers have given test replies to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
Sure enough, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Detecting lies, or “locating lies,” is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charade, where the goal is to exclaim, “I have you,” deception detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades at prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the findings of the research is that the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look into the eyes.
They do not always stutter, babble, blush or restlessly.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, questioning, and timing.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel comfortable, handling their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more “self-oriented lies,” while women tell more “other-oriented” lies—usually to protect someone’s feelings—that married people lie less frequently to their partners than people who aren’t married (but the lies they tend to tell tend to be “self-oriented”).
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called “creating a baseline.”
It helps to provide benchmarks to measure changes afterwards.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
It’s best to know if someone normally kicks with their foot all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when they see their feet kicking in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for misleading, verbal, and nonverbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as warning signs, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze their upper body while trying to remember their story, can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit “post-interview relief” — that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Often interrogators falsely make it appear that the interview has ended just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up and used past time while claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: “I didn’t have sex with that woman...Miss Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone may use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to my understanding."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding being victimized by the scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
Controversial pipeline plan diverted following threat of US delay in approval
Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico — infuriating unions while appeasing environmentalists — the company seeking to build the pipeline says it is willing to redirect the project to reroute it.
TransCanada said Monday night that it will move the planned pipeline out of the ecologically sensitive Sandhills area in Nebraska, and is confident the project will win approval.
The company announced the decision at a press conference at the Nebraska Capitol.
TransCanada CEO Alex Pourbax says the company remains confident that the pipeline will eventually be approved, albeit on a different route.
This follows last week’s announcement by the State Department that they would delay the decision on a federal permit for the project until new potential routes are studied to avoid the Sandhills areas of Nebraska and the Ogallala aquifer, a vast groundwater supply.
"This is a real path of progress," Rep. Lee Terry, a Republican from Nebraska, told Fox News.
The new environmental review ordered by the State Department is likely to set aside any decision until 2013, after next year’s election, although officials denied the policy was involved in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as the State Department’s request, and expressed their full support.
The 1,700-kilometer pipeline would stretch from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would take 700,000 barrels per day from the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
For this, it would be necessary to cross six states.
It is hated by environmentalists, but loved by working groups, which have bet on the estimated 20,000 jobs linked to the pipeline.
But Nebraska lawmakers opposed to the plan are weighing legislation to force a move away from the Sandhills region and the Ogallala aquifer, the largest source of drinking water and irrigation.
The State Department’s current environmental impact study found that the project posed only limited adverse environmental impacts, but the energy industry source said the department’s inspector general has ordered an independent test of the review process, focusing on two issues.
One is whether TransCanada-hired lobbyist Paul Elliot, who served as Hillary Clinton’s campaign adviser in 2008, represents a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a firm that was hired to direct the original study was an inappropriate choice because it was linked to TransCanada.
