A New York family claims disco diva Patti LaBelle behaved like a madwoman in the lobby of her Manhattan building, terrifying her little daughter to the point that she threw up in fear.
The "Lady Marmalade" singer's diatribe frightened 18-month-old Genevieve Monk so much that she suffered "personality changes, sleep disorders" and "increased her fear of strangers," her family says in Manhattan's Supreme Court.
It was November 10 last year when trampoline rider Kevin Monk, his wife, Roseanna, a kindergarten teacher, and Genevieve were preparing to go on a family trip.
While Kevin Monk was picking up the car, Roseanna Monk descended to the lobby of the Riverside Boulevard building, with her luggage, carrying Genevieve.
Roseanna Monk said she stood near the door and put her daughter on the floor for a moment.
"Someone came up from behind and said, 'Do you know what your daughter is doing?' I said, 'Yes,' and went to get her,'" she said.
LaBelle angrily admonished the pregnant woman.
“She said in an aggressive tone, ‘I shouldn’t have left her daughter near the door,’” Roseanna Monk said.
"I said, 'I have no interest in what you say or think.'
He got angry and started using bad words - the word C and the word J aloud...
