Climate adversity slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez’s administration, unemployment and informality in Sinaloa have increased, foreign investment has fallen and the economy has contracted.
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, self-described change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances in the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, no growth is observed, instead there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing million-dollar losses for the agricultural sector, limited the chances of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of overall economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic drop of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost damage, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there were damages in 582,835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent had partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a constant increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated growth, since while from January to March 55,053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53% of the Economically Active Population.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out since public policy.
"What you're seeing is a rise in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the effects of a resource restriction by legislation that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, and for people who take dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work them, invest them and use them in something," he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes pointed out that in the increase in unemployment there is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state looking for work abroad in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties to enter, and second because entering already have many difficulties to find work, those people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the Sinaloa labor market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state works without being contributing as a worker to any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the state’s labor lags are low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Security.
The average monthly income of the Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5,352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7,375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
In addition to the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 there is the largest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Ministry of Economy from January to June of the state FDI totaled 630,697 dollars, which represents a fall of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143,312 dollars recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Secretariat of Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17.28 billion pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the state government in July requested the approval of a credit of 3 billion pesos, which would be destined to investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to reactivate the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2.6 billion pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of debt in any sector of the economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of Mario López Valdés’ government shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensely to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, we have failed to align the effort of everyone and above all the good progress already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year halted the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frost, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn around fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining the Vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said that it is necessary to direct the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that work has been done, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and the economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated," he said.
Work to be done
The president of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better guides the Government’s efforts.
"In general terms I would say that the Government has been striving to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there is some progress but it is important that a long-term program is developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in its way of conducting public policy.
