I’ve only been to Costa Rica once and on vacation; it’s such a beautiful country and I think we’re going to be able to stay a few days there.
So we’re excited to bring our music there.
I ask because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live intensely the days before.
What do they say to their most fervent followers?
Thank you for standing by our side through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve played over the last 21 years have happened over the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of gigantic shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We’re really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did they discover Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have many friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends always went surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; that’s how we found out, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, they’ve been delivering huge shows with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's the reason for this?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played for a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we might have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour, they are celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe all they have achieved?
Yes, absolutely.
“First of all, I don’t think any of us imagined we’d be in a great rock band and having done it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We keep counting our blessings and are very excited that we can continue making music together.
We all love each other and we love making music.
We are fortunate to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean for you to have been a fundamental part of the emergence of grunge?
It’s always been an honor to be part of that group of great bands.
We are very close friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s surprising when a move comes from a group of friends and it’s a rare occurrence.
Occasionally, a band emerges from a city, but it’s much stranger when five or ten bands leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to be friends with all of them still and we’re honored to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It’s also very strange that a band like yours will stay together and with the same members for so long.
Yeah, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is much longer than many bands last.
Firstly, I think we are all lucky to be still alive and, secondly, we all care about each other.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also been opened that give freedom to each one to experience.
We trust each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you don’t be too touring because it’s easy to fall for that game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for the music, that reminds you that you should respect the music and what it brought, without infatuation with being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was a great thing.
We were a band for almost three years and never released a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were a lot of frustrations because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we are still very close friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a photo I think about the amazing person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that’s why you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with various proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we are looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that comes to mind.
As a bassist, what are your influences?
There are so many.
Among the first I can think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant even though it’s no longer a fashion?
I think we all always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that came out at the same time, and, if there’s relevance now, I think it’s a wonderful thing because it’s music that’s worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It’s interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that maybe feel lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs although they can sound a bit positive.
With both, when Ed touched them, I cried when I heard them and they are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there’s some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs certainly represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
Peru:
Fujimori hospitalized again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to be assessed for loss of muscle strength in his legs, his GP said.
Fujimori, 72, who serves a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his government (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including a cancer of the tongue for which he has been operated four times and which remains under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Channel N television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength of his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He was operated four times for cancer of the tongue, has a weight loss of 18 kilos to which other pathologies have been added such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been detained since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Special Operations of the police.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people at the hands of an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the early years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official entourage, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and made up of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayans residing in Mexico, according to the agenda disseminated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "propitious for the exchange of information in all that is political affairs between the two nations", as published by the presidency of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call to consult its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has presided since November over the G20, a group made up of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world, and has an agreement with the South American country since January this year to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the implementation of tax exchange agreements in order to leave the “grey list” of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), formed by countries that did not implement all international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
At the trade level, Mexico and Uruguay have a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004 that has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The mustache plumber passes the three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought, tirelessly, over 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before had it done in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which arrives this month in stores around the world, has been designed from the beginning to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS portable system, which allows you to play in three dimensions without wearing glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how stereoscopy without glasses should work," Nintendo's head of specialized press in Spain, Omar <0xC3><0x81>lvarez, said during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Alvarez said "Super Mario 3D Land" is "Nintendo's first video game originally designed for that support", as hits such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesperson has argued that, despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is a video game "accessible" that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
<0xC3><0x81>lvarez has stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to engage less skilled users.
Once passed, the more experienced will be able to give a "second turn" to the game levels, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions to be able to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This incursion of Super Mario in the three dimensions also means the return of the character to a portable console, a fact that did not occur since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo nods to the fans of the saga and repeats the formula of the success of the previous installments, consisting in that the plumber of the mustache will have to travel platforms mined of dangers in order to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find new moves, environments, costumes and enemies and also a "playable" Luigi.
Colom endorses Portillo's extradition to the United States
President <0xC3><0x81>lvaro Colom announced Tuesday that he has extradited former ruler Alfonso Portillo to the United States to answer for the conspiracy to launder $70 million.
Thus ends the process for Guatemala to respond to the request of the northern country that claimed Portillo to judge him there.
At a press conference, Colom said his decision is due to the independence of judicial and executive powers, taking into account that a sentencing court had already ordered the extradition.
He said that during his tenure he “did not get his hands on” judicial decisions and gave way to all the extraditions he has known.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín, for murder and serious injuries, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking, will be extradited.
The move by Colom is an executive procedure after all the judicial and constitutional bodies have been exhausted to prosecute the former president from 2000 to 2004.
According to decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Court of Constitutionality (CC), Portillo must be extradited once he has solved his legal situation in Guatemala and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of the embezzlement of Q120 million in the Ministry of Defense when he was president, which was the process leading up to extradition, but the Public Prosecutor’s Office appealed and reactivated the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people at risk
The entity was born to avoid the fall in the marginality of untrained children
The balance of the first 25 years of life of the social support entity Trinijove is important: 6,000 young people at risk of exclusion have received help to overcome a difficult situation throughout this quarter century.
To this is added the hundreds of jobs currently obtained for this social group.
The anniversary served yesterday to take stock of an event held in the former Fabra i Coats factory complex attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was born in the neighborhood of Trinitat Vella in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with little training, without work, with problems of graduation or in a situation of falling into marginality.
The celebration yesterday in Sant Andreu concentrated a large number of leaders of entities and institutions that in these 25 years have collaborated with the association.
The varied political representation, in full electoral time, showed the unitary character of the work done by Trinijove.
Together with the president of the Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the event was attended by the former socialist education councillor, Ernest Maragall, and the former mayor and current ecosocialist councillor Ricard Gomà.
Also attending the large hall of La Fabra i Coats were the current Minister of Social Welfare and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the general director of the social work of La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas said that Trinijove was born in a very difficult time and that the current one is too, but added that the work done so far "is a good base".
The president cited Trinijove as an example for his ability to fight bad circumstances and to give hope to people in difficulty.
"The crisis is not something new for the entity and for the work it does," he said.
Evicted a squatted farm where macro parties were held
The invaders had taken possession of 11 of the 13 floors of the building, in Balmes, 51.
The 12 occupants left the farm at noon yesterday without offering resistance
Everything seems to indicate that the nightmare that the neighbors of 51 Balmes Street were living has come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left yesterday noon the building they illegally occupied, and where they organized macrofiestas that desperately the neighborhood, by court order and without the need for police intervention.
When the operation was finished, the door lock was changed to prevent the situation from repeating itself.
“From now on there will be access control,” the administrator said.
The squatters, who had invaded 11 of the 13 floors of the building - the rest are inhabited - took away all the electrical installation and part of the water, as well as painting the walls and leaving waste of all kinds, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
The first three floors were the scene of the crowded parties, which lasted up to two days and despaired the tenants.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which has also been damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that since the building was occupied the business has fallen by 80%.
The owner of the nightclub points out that the invaders of the farm were unfair competition, since they sold the drinks for three euros, while in the nightclub they are worth 10.
In addition, the owner of the leisure venue had had to respond to neighborhood complaints for noise, while, she said, the inconvenience is not caused by the customers of the disco, but by the inhabitants of the occupied house and, above all, the attendees of the parties that were organized there, which had increased in frequency and intensity in recent weeks, according to angry neighbors of the area.
The head of the club explained that the inconvenience was so great that she even reached an agreement with the owner of the property and for nine months she "forgave" the rent.
The Urban Guard also confirmed that in recent weeks it had received more complaints from neighbors about the situation.
The president of the municipal group of the PP in the city council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had claimed last week "immediately evict the property to end the problems of coexistence and civics that produce neighbors, as well as the degradation of the area."
The popular leader explained that before the summer there was only one floor of the building occupied, but over the last few months the squatters had been entering all the floors of the building and almost all the floors, and that in some there have even been robberies.
In this sense, he added that, "it is necessary to end impunity and be forceful against the incivility that has been generated on the farm."
Also yesterday, the Mossos evicted a building in Nou Barris.
At 1530 hours, police arrived at 35 rue de Mont-ral, after receiving a call from a neighbour who had observed four people entering the building.
All four were arrested at the time.
