Asphalt from UNAM would avoid bumps
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of the UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the signals sent by the pavement were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 potholes each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement is adequate, the potholes could be completely reduced or even eliminated.
In his lecture A Technological Opinion of Potholes, issued in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory in charge of his development developed modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with a greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, near 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but that it is modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The CF researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt wallet, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
As vehicles travel and effort is generated, it allows forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On top of the asphalt binder, a last layer is placed called rolling binder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that also bathes in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt binder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and diffuse the efforts, the rolling folder also requires to have the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt binder.
When the soil is moistened, the water diffuses into the interior of the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a pothole, he said, the first to wear is the rolling film and only then the asphalt binder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The also member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicular load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always be in relation to the vehicular load and ensure that it is complied with, to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to research and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already even on the market and allow to repair potholes easily and without using high temperatures.
