This is one of the findings of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which involved six experts from a variety of fields, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when the patient considers this option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
For starters, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks 10th, the study notes that “the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the issue of death.”
With or without medication, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And even though most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded by Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in hospitals.
With regard to the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that did not agree with the position of the federal Government, which had already stated that it did not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not resulted in an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with incompetent or non-consensual persons.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
In Canada, euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal.
“In Canada, assisted suicide is practiced, although it is clearly illegal,” explains Jocelyn Downie.
