85% of Canadians have already spoken out in favor of euthanasia, since they believe it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 survey by Angus Reid.
In addition, 66% believe that the legalization of euthanasia will not imply that the lives of elderly or disabled people have less value.
As for people who have committed assisted suicide, 41 per cent of respondents believe that no proceedings should be instituted against them.
In relation to the maintenance or interruption of health care for a patient, the situation is not so clear, according to the authors of the report.
In addition, among their recommendations, they suggest that the Criminal Code should state that the withdrawal of health care, if it has been legally refused, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The expert committee also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses care at the end of his or her life without fear of facing a complaint.
On palliative care, the committee calls for governments, healthcare institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just in cancer cases.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee calls for it to be considered euthanasia and to undergo the same procedures unless it serves to reduce physical pain.
