We know, since Napoleon "the Little One", that it was a matter of thought.
Universal suffrage, although a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and a control of powers, an education, Lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this regard, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return of the political sphere, but also the worrying sense of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence needs to be addressed in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer advancing in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to the needs and in a disorderly way.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a blank stop to the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to draw blows of effect, but a common, full-fledged, quiet and continuous exercise of options and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that submits to the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, the one that suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers humiliation in the international sphere.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is for popular sovereignty to regain the helm of the European project.
Because only together can Europeans reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare their future through investments.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
Having long fought against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
Let it be so.
But to think of it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by the citizens, would be new madness and would lead us to a new deadlock.
We must take on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" republicans.
Interest-driven revolution would not be enough.
This lesson still applies.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
The only way to achieve this is to build a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European people's sovereignty.
To build Europe, let us make Europeans.
Cards with "contactless" chip become generalized
The world chip card show opens Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global sales of cards with microprocessors (bank cards, phones with SIM cards, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to calculations of the Eurosmart cabinet.
The most powerful segment is that of contactless technology, which allows you to pay for public transport or purchases simply by bringing the card closer to a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its share is expected to increase further in 2012 (580 million units are expected) and account for about 10% of the global chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe, which has long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the contactless payment sector.
Around 26 million Visa bank cards already have this feature, which is accepted in 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards are being used.
But large surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCard Pass cards this year.
To get the upper gear, however, it is necessary for banks to make them available to their customers.
“There are two large French establishments that have committed to systematically disseminate, in the future, among their customers, bank cards equipped with the contactless system,” announced Gérard Nébouy, Managing Director of Visa Europe France.
Banks test mobile phone payment
But it is only a first step towards the payment method of the future: the mobile phone.
Currently, there are few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, indispensable to carry out transactions.
"They're lagging behind."
“But I should finally experience a real boom next year.”
“We expect between 80 and 120 million units to be sold worldwide in 2012,” said Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
The bank Crédit agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhones of around 200 customers and collaborators will be equipped with a case that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
The Société générale also said yesterday that it is preparing to commercialize an offer that allows its customers to pay contactless via their mobile phone.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-suspected ties between the Al Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian Boko Haram sect have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Algiers already “has the certainty.”
“The way both organizations operate and intelligence reports show that they are cooperating,” he said, without elaborating.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the runways.
Abducted at a restaurant in Niamey by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips that belonged to the terrorists.
Axis terrorists
The study of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers particularly captured the interest of the investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who remained for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is supposedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is progress, but we certainly have to wait for more formal evidence before we talk about operational cooperation between AQMI and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and that it is increasingly active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "supports" had become increasingly evident in the evolution and discourses of Boko Haram or in its operational modes, which now involve the use of suicide bombers or explosive devices increasingly complex and in the same style as those used by AQMI.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pressuring Abuja to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long regarded the group as an illuminated community of little interest.
A rapid success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in Hausa, “Western education is a sin”), incites the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Muslim Nigeria.
In this poor region, the partnership is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes and demands strict respect for sharia, while its militants launch into the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are oriented in the first place to the churches, the bars, the administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were especially active and attacks on police stations multiplied.
Abuja’s reaction was, as is often the case, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested while alive, is killed in prison.
Since then, the sect is radicalized and abandons its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, he claimed responsibility for an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and then another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuja, in particular the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations becomes its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which would span from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, is disturbing for all security experts.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and Al-Chebab Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the centre of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to “share all the information.”
The world according to Republican presidential candidates
In relation to China, Iran and aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry rival in simplicity and lack of knowledge.
A crisis-weakened America, can it manage a complex world with simple or even simplistic ideas?
By listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might think so.
