And, arguing that it takes economic rebuilding of America to resurrect his leadership, Obama gives the impression of being fairer.
The Nord Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly with Russia via the Baltic Sea floor, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on the banks of the Baltic Sea, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first 1,224 km tee connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipe is expected to be completed by the end of 2012 to supply a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow to supply gas directly to Germany, avoiding the land route by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe’s energy, given that the project has generated a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large consumers of gas and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically unites us,” Fillon said at the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the directors of Gazprom, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to take extreme measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Swedish waters, but the project managers renounced it as the Swedes were unwilling to allow a Russian state-owned company to settle permanently at sea off its coast.
“In the event of a breakdown, we will stop the gas flow in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, since they have predicted joints that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, entrained by a ship, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by the pressure.
At the beginning it is 200 bars and at the output of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to that company, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, all of its gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the full capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually transported," Müller said.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of shareholders and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not surpass their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of expenses.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy pine-planted coastline.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to restore people’s taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as if aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch on the market a notebook of design, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was in charge of launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century, to the current taste," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Modo Modo.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Away has been the confidential production of the early years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had twelve employees at the beginning, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and has been able to impose his identity.
“We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the boom in emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Disheartening?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.
At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times higher than the average.
“However, there is still a lot to be done.”
It is worth mentioning that the disabled unemployed continue to face numerous obstacles to accessing employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 (average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In other words, there are numerous issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that "are the crux of the problem", says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people’s mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité noted that the surveyed directors have “a low level of knowledge about disabilities”, with an “excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled”.
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest figures available, which date from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
“Now we have reached around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees in their workforce, compared to 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
Hazard: "A joy"
About to face the Bleus on Tuesday night (20h45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens do not hide the pleasure generated by this friendly match.
We will not dare to say that there was connivance between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting side by side, on the stand of the Stade de France auditorium, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have really made peace.
Five months after his striker’s grudge gesture against Turkey, the Belgian coach has nothing but praise for him.
"I was very happy for Eden, for his progress and for being Belgian."
“I want to move forward,” the Lille striker replies.
As for the contrast between his presentations in his team and in the selection, "it's a set," he has been justified.
“I’m in Lille all year round, which doesn’t apply to Belgium.
"I have to stand."
Called to play against Romania on Friday night, taking into account this match against France, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis to finally "shine".
Not to mention the “pleasure”.
He has been cheering the Bleus since he was seven years old, as well as during the victorious campaigns of 1998 and 2000.
“I’ve always been his fan,” he says.
Certainly, this will reinforce especially the "special" character of the meeting.
Especially because he will face "Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami)", he recalls.
“We just faced each other recently.
"Playing against them is always a joy."
With simplicity, Leekens has for his part made reference to "pride".
"Pride" for playing "a gala game."
"Pride" also for verifying, as "neighbor", that France "returns to be a very high level team", about a year after the trauma of Knysna.
“Laurent Blanc has done a formidable job,” he said enthusiastically.
While Belgium will not be attending the next European competition, the coach would be delighted to be able to share a plane with the Bleus towards... Brazil, in 2014.
“Our little Belgians are growing,” he said.
“We’re building something; the players are ambitious, they’re hungry.
"You can see it in the next matches." Including the match against France.
Portugal shows a lot of confidence
Paulo Bento's Portugal face with great optimism the return match against Bosnia (22h00), which will be held on Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the first leg, both teams lacked realism.
"When these 90 minutes pass, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country."
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
He has no doubts; the Selecçao, which he has been running since September 2010, is going to qualify for Euro 2012.
In fact, only 90 minutes separate Portugal from happiness.
But there is a match to play and a rival, Bosnia, to defeat.
Considering the one-way match (0-0), Friday in Zenica’s hell, it seems clear that the thing is not decided.
Portugal dominated the match for more than an hour, yes, but could not score the valuable goal that would have given him peace of mind.
"It's a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we haven't scored away from home."
But at home, in the luminous Estádio da Luz in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced that they will pass, in front of an audience that should be just as enthusiastic, even if it is evident that the match "is very equal ", said an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We hope the match will be very even, but we are completely convinced that we can take the lead," said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
“We still have a 50% chance of participating in Euro 2012,” said Queiroz’s successor.
Friday's draw in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
The Bosnians could get a draw, but they also need to score.
"It's a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we haven't scored away from home," Bento said.
"We are going to play against a team that has a great technical quality and that has players with a great individual quality," he added.
